If you are huge on fusion style of flavor explosion, this may not be the place for you. This place exceeds more in simplicity and authenticity. Good sushi should not need a lot of flavor embellishments in order to taste good which Kaz Sushi Bistro exemplifies. Do not expect to feel "full" unless you plan to spend a lot of money; this is a great place for providing very good food to the "satiated" level which is just perfect. As for service, just expect it to be slower on the weekend. Unfortunately, I was just in a hurry to pay my bill. I will definitely come back on a more calm day. So I am from Philadelphia and eat sushi on a regular basis. Apparently my area is well known for it's high quality sushi as I am told from people who visit the area. I was traveling to visit family in DC and heavily researched sushi in advanced and stumped upon Kaz being highly recommended.  The pros: Beautiful atmosphere and building, the inside looked like an upscale restaurant that only DCs finest would frequent. The clientele was of equal status as everyone seemed well off, dressed well, and had good conversations.  The service was also top notch. The servers were friendly, professional, and prompt we barely waited to be sat or even server food.  The cons: The menu was extremely limited. Their entire sushi and sashimi line up fit on 1 page. In Philadelphia we have what feels like an encyclopedia of sushi choices that span every possible combination.  The sushi itself did not taste that great. They put questionable additions to our rolls such as cilantro which I thought was only for tacos. The rolls themselves were so tiny and small that it didnt fill anyone up. The rolls seemed to be half the size of what we were used to. All three members of my party had to order a pizza when we got home because we were not full by any stretch of the imagination.

While in DC, my husband and I decided to make reservations at KAZ and try their omakase dinner. You have the option to have their pre-selected menus for a set price at the table, or partake in their a la carte omakase experience at the sushi bar. We opted for the sushi bar, and it was incredible. One sushi chef was dedicated to just us, fixing plate after plate of beautiful and fresh sashimi, nigiri, and assorted small dishes. For each round, he recommended how to eat each item (no soy, with hands, etc etc). He was very nice, and the entire experience was phenomenal. He requested that we let him know when we are content, but still have room for dessert. He finished out our meal with a lovely green tea cheese cake, and raspberry Jello cake filled with chocolate. Everything tasted delicious, and was beautifully plated. The price is higher than some other sushi restaurants, but the quality is also far better. The portions were generous, with large pieces of fish, and the rice was perfectly soft.  If we go back to DC, we will definitely be coming here again.
